</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Surgical mesh is used most frequently for tension-free repair of abdominal wall hernias in adults, because the rate of hernia recurrence is lower with mesh than with primary soft-tissue repair. Since the introduction of polypropylene mesh in the middle of the 20th century, many mesh materials and configurations for specific surgical procedures have been developed. In addition to abdominal wall hernia repair, mesh may be used for repair of diaphragmatic hernias, urinary incontinence in women (female slings), genitourinary prolapse (vaginal mesh and sacrocolpopexy), rectal prolapse (rectopexy), and postprostatectomy male urinary incontinence (male slings). General mesh repair complications include chronic pain; fluid collections such as seromas, hematomas, and abscesses; adhesions that may lead to intestinal blockage; erosion into solid or hollow viscera including enterocutaneous fistulizing disease; and mesh failure characterized by mesh shrinkage, detachment, and migration with repair malfunction. Several mesh complications are often diagnosed with imaging, primarily with CT and less frequently with MRI and US, despite variable mesh visibility at imaging. This article reviews the common surgical mesh applications in the abdomen and pelvis, discusses imaging of mesh repair complications, and provides complication treatment highlights.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2020</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2020190106">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2020190106">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig1a.jpeg" height="1328" width="1773" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span>. Normal variable appearance of ventral hernia mesh repair in three patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image in a 46-year-old man with mesh repair of an incisional hernia shows hyperattenuating expanded polytetrafluoroethylene mesh (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image in a 67-year-old man with a ventral abdominal hernia repaired with expanded polytetrafluoroethylene mesh shows hyperattenuating expanded polytetrafluoroethylene mesh (arrows) with fluid (<b>*</b>) trapped between the mesh and the abdominal wall. Trapped fluid was stable at imaging for many years, and the patient was asymptomatic. A small amount of trapped fluid may remain as a normal finding. <b>(c)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image in a 72-year-old woman after mesh repair of a large ventral hernia with the mesh, a fully resorbable monofilament mesh made of poly-4-hydroxybuterate. Arrowhead = site of hernia mesh repair; the mesh is not discernible.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig1b.jpeg" height="1328" width="1769" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span>. Normal variable appearance of ventral hernia mesh repair in three patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image in a 46-year-old man with mesh repair of an incisional hernia shows hyperattenuating expanded polytetrafluoroethylene mesh (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image in a 67-year-old man with a ventral abdominal hernia repaired with expanded polytetrafluoroethylene mesh shows hyperattenuating expanded polytetrafluoroethylene mesh (arrows) with fluid (<b>*</b>) trapped between the mesh and the abdominal wall. Trapped fluid was stable at imaging for many years, and the patient was asymptomatic. A small amount of trapped fluid may remain as a normal finding. <b>(c)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image in a 72-year-old woman after mesh repair of a large ventral hernia with the mesh, a fully resorbable monofilament mesh made of poly-4-hydroxybuterate. Arrowhead = site of hernia mesh repair; the mesh is not discernible.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig1c.jpeg" height="1351" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig1c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1c</span>. Normal variable appearance of ventral hernia mesh repair in three patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image in a 46-year-old man with mesh repair of an incisional hernia shows hyperattenuating expanded polytetrafluoroethylene mesh (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image in a 67-year-old man with a ventral abdominal hernia repaired with expanded polytetrafluoroethylene mesh shows hyperattenuating expanded polytetrafluoroethylene mesh (arrows) with fluid (<b>*</b>) trapped between the mesh and the abdominal wall. Trapped fluid was stable at imaging for many years, and the patient was asymptomatic. A small amount of trapped fluid may remain as a normal finding. <b>(c)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image in a 72-year-old woman after mesh repair of a large ventral hernia with the mesh, a fully resorbable monofilament mesh made of poly-4-hydroxybuterate. Arrowhead = site of hernia mesh repair; the mesh is not discernible.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig1c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig2.jpeg" height="1200" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span>. Axial contrast material–enhanced CT image in a 61-year-old man with bilateral inguinal hernia mesh plug repair shows the normal appearance of bilateral mesh plugs (arrows) located near the external iliac arteries and veins and lateral to the inferior epigastric arteries (arrowheads), which may simulate lymphadenopathy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig3.jpeg" height="1125" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig3" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3</span>. Normal MRI appearance of mesh. Axial T2-weighted MR image in an 80-year-old man with flat mesh repair of bilateral inguinal hernias shows slightly wavy T2-hypointense mesh (arrows) in the anterior pelvis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig4a.jpeg" height="1351" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. Normal meshoma appearance in a 31-year-old woman after liver transplant who underwent repair of a ventral abdominal hernia with a fully absorbable biomaterial mesh made of polyglycolic acid and trimethylene carbonate copolymer. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a meshoma (arrows), which is a curvilinear soft-tissue thickening without separately visible mesh. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial T2-weighted <b>(b)</b> and axial T1-weighted fat-saturated contrast-enhanced <b>(c)</b> MR images show the meshoma, which is hypointense (arrows in <b>b</b>) and shows contrast enhancement (arrowheads in <b>c</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig4b.jpeg" height="1332" width="1766" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. Normal meshoma appearance in a 31-year-old woman after liver transplant who underwent repair of a ventral abdominal hernia with a fully absorbable biomaterial mesh made of polyglycolic acid and trimethylene carbonate copolymer. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a meshoma (arrows), which is a curvilinear soft-tissue thickening without separately visible mesh. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial T2-weighted <b>(b)</b> and axial T1-weighted fat-saturated contrast-enhanced <b>(c)</b> MR images show the meshoma, which is hypointense (arrows in <b>b</b>) and shows contrast enhancement (arrowheads in <b>c</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig4c.jpeg" height="1332" width="1776" aria-labelledby="fig4c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4c</span>. Normal meshoma appearance in a 31-year-old woman after liver transplant who underwent repair of a ventral abdominal hernia with a fully absorbable biomaterial mesh made of polyglycolic acid and trimethylene carbonate copolymer. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a meshoma (arrows), which is a curvilinear soft-tissue thickening without separately visible mesh. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial T2-weighted <b>(b)</b> and axial T1-weighted fat-saturated contrast-enhanced <b>(c)</b> MR images show the meshoma, which is hypointense (arrows in <b>b</b>) and shows contrast enhancement (arrowheads in <b>c</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig4c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig5a.jpeg" height="798" width="1599" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span>. Normal US appearance of mesh in two patients without hernia recurrence or bulging. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal US image acquired during the Valsalva maneuver in a 38-year-old man after right inguinal hernia repair shows the hyperechoic linear appearance of the mesh (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Transverse US image acquired during the Valsalva maneuver in a 50-year-old man with a right lower-quadrant ventral abdominal hernia repair shows normal slightly wavy appearance of the mesh (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig5b.jpeg" height="1200" width="1601" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span>. Normal US appearance of mesh in two patients without hernia recurrence or bulging. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal US image acquired during the Valsalva maneuver in a 38-year-old man after right inguinal hernia repair shows the hyperechoic linear appearance of the mesh (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Transverse US image acquired during the Valsalva maneuver in a 50-year-old man with a right lower-quadrant ventral abdominal hernia repair shows normal slightly wavy appearance of the mesh (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig6.jpeg" height="1606" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig6" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6</span>. Illustration shows different anatomic planes for placement of abdominal wall mesh. For overlay placement (red), the mesh is placed superficial to the anterior rectus sheath (<i>ars</i>). For inlay placement (green), the mesh edges are sutured to edges of the fascial defect. For retrorectus placement (blue), the mesh is placed in the prefascial space between the rectus muscle and the posterior rectus sheath (<i>prs</i>). For preperitoneal placement (orange), the mesh is placed deep to the posterior rectus sheath and superficial to the transversalis fascia. For underlay placement (purple), the mesh is placed intraperitoneally. <i>sqf</i> = subcutaneous fat, <i>tp</i> = transversalis fascia and peritoneum (combined).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig6">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig7a.jpeg" height="1201" width="1606" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. Mesh-associated fluid collections. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image in an 80-year-old man with umbilical hernia mesh repair (arrowhead) shows a thick-walled subcutaneous collection (arrow). Aspiration showed that it was a sterile seroma. <b>(b)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image in a 59-year-old man shows umbilical hernia mesh repair (arrowhead) and a thick-walled fluid collection in the anterior abdominal wall (arrow). Aspiration yielded pus. Imaging alone does not allow differentiation of sterile from infected postoperative fluid collections.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig7b.jpeg" height="1200" width="1540" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. Mesh-associated fluid collections. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image in an 80-year-old man with umbilical hernia mesh repair (arrowhead) shows a thick-walled subcutaneous collection (arrow). Aspiration showed that it was a sterile seroma. <b>(b)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image in a 59-year-old man shows umbilical hernia mesh repair (arrowhead) and a thick-walled fluid collection in the anterior abdominal wall (arrow). Aspiration yielded pus. Imaging alone does not allow differentiation of sterile from infected postoperative fluid collections.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig8.jpeg" height="1125" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig8" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span>. Wound dehiscence and mesh exposure in a 53-year-old man who presented 2 weeks after mesh repair of an incarcerated ventral hernia with exposed mesh and pus draining from the wound. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows fluid between the thin hyperattenuating layers of the mesh (arrowheads). Arrows indicate the dehiscent margins of the incision with the gap covered by a wound vacuum device (*).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig8">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig9a.jpeg" height="1181" width="1572" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Postsurgical granulomatous reaction in an 81-year-old man with a history of prostate cancer, resected cholangiocarcinoma, and newly diagnosed urothelial carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows abdominal wall mesh, which is visible as a thin hyperattenuating line (arrowheads), and large ascites, which was suspicious for carcinomatosis. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows an enhancing nodule (arrow) adjacent to a surgical clip in the deep pelvis, which was also concerning for carcinomatosis. Extensive studding of the peritoneum (also suspicious for carcinomatosis) was found at surgery (this was not apparent at imaging, with the exception of this pelvic nodule). Biopsy results showed that the nodule was granulomatous reaction. The surgeon believed that the the mesh caused the reaction and removed it.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig9b.jpeg" height="1181" width="1575" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. Postsurgical granulomatous reaction in an 81-year-old man with a history of prostate cancer, resected cholangiocarcinoma, and newly diagnosed urothelial carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows abdominal wall mesh, which is visible as a thin hyperattenuating line (arrowheads), and large ascites, which was suspicious for carcinomatosis. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows an enhancing nodule (arrow) adjacent to a surgical clip in the deep pelvis, which was also concerning for carcinomatosis. Extensive studding of the peritoneum (also suspicious for carcinomatosis) was found at surgery (this was not apparent at imaging, with the exception of this pelvic nodule). Biopsy results showed that the nodule was granulomatous reaction. The surgeon believed that the the mesh caused the reaction and removed it.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig10a.jpeg" height="1544" width="1501" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. Mesh-associated fistulizing disease in three different patients with anterior abdominal wall mesh. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image in a 63-year-old woman shows a small bowel fistula (arrow) with oral contrast material leaking into an abscess (arrowhead) deep to the transversalis fascia. The mesh is invisible. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image in a 67-year-old woman shows an enterocutaneous fistulous tract (arrows) with foci of gas extending to the skin surface. The mesh is barely visible (arrowhead). <b>(c)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image in a 52-year-old man with purulent drainage from the anterior abdominal wall shows extensive inflammatory changes of the soft tissues with a thin pocket of gas and leaked enteric contrast material (arrow) from the adjacent transverse colon (arrowhead). The mesh is invisible.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig10b.jpeg" height="1455" width="1486" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. Mesh-associated fistulizing disease in three different patients with anterior abdominal wall mesh. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image in a 63-year-old woman shows a small bowel fistula (arrow) with oral contrast material leaking into an abscess (arrowhead) deep to the transversalis fascia. The mesh is invisible. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image in a 67-year-old woman shows an enterocutaneous fistulous tract (arrows) with foci of gas extending to the skin surface. The mesh is barely visible (arrowhead). <b>(c)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image in a 52-year-old man with purulent drainage from the anterior abdominal wall shows extensive inflammatory changes of the soft tissues with a thin pocket of gas and leaked enteric contrast material (arrow) from the adjacent transverse colon (arrowhead). The mesh is invisible.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig10c.jpeg" height="1455" width="1456" aria-labelledby="fig10c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10c</span>. Mesh-associated fistulizing disease in three different patients with anterior abdominal wall mesh. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image in a 63-year-old woman shows a small bowel fistula (arrow) with oral contrast material leaking into an abscess (arrowhead) deep to the transversalis fascia. The mesh is invisible. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image in a 67-year-old woman shows an enterocutaneous fistulous tract (arrows) with foci of gas extending to the skin surface. The mesh is barely visible (arrowhead). <b>(c)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image in a 52-year-old man with purulent drainage from the anterior abdominal wall shows extensive inflammatory changes of the soft tissues with a thin pocket of gas and leaked enteric contrast material (arrow) from the adjacent transverse colon (arrowhead). The mesh is invisible.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig10c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig11a.jpeg" height="1325" width="1326" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. Mesh failure in two different patients with recurrent bulging. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal nonenhanced CT image in a 42-year-old man shows mesh detachment with recurrent hernia. The detached free edge of the mesh (arrowhead) is at the superior aspect of the recurrent hernia (arrow), which contains the small bowel and colon. <b>(b)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image in a 52-year-old man shows expansion of the 10-year-old mesh (arrowheads) with bulging of mesenteric contents at the midline (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig11b.jpeg" height="1325" width="1324" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span>. Mesh failure in two different patients with recurrent bulging. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal nonenhanced CT image in a 42-year-old man shows mesh detachment with recurrent hernia. The detached free edge of the mesh (arrowhead) is at the superior aspect of the recurrent hernia (arrow), which contains the small bowel and colon. <b>(b)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image in a 52-year-old man shows expansion of the 10-year-old mesh (arrowheads) with bulging of mesenteric contents at the midline (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig12.jpeg" height="740" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12</span>. Mesh bulging at US. Transverse US image during the Valsalva maneuver in a 36-year-old man with new bulging at the site of a flat mesh inguinal hernia repair. The hyperechoic linear shadowing mesh shows bulging (arrows) during the Valsalva maneuver lateral to the deep inferior epigastric vessels (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig13a.jpeg" height="1180" width="1575" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span>. Inguinal hernia plug pseudolesion in a 72-year-old man with a remote right inguinal hernia plug repair who underwent PET/CT for multiple myeloma. <b>(a)</b> Axial fused PET/CT image shows a hypermetabolic nodule in the anterior right pelvis (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image shows a masslike low-attenuating structure in the anterior right pelvis (arrowhead) that is the typical appearance of a plugoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig13b.jpeg" height="1180" width="1573" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span>. Inguinal hernia plug pseudolesion in a 72-year-old man with a remote right inguinal hernia plug repair who underwent PET/CT for multiple myeloma. <b>(a)</b> Axial fused PET/CT image shows a hypermetabolic nodule in the anterior right pelvis (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image shows a masslike low-attenuating structure in the anterior right pelvis (arrowhead) that is the typical appearance of a plugoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig14a.jpeg" height="1323" width="1323" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span>. Hematoma in two different patients. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image in a 60-year-old man with pain and swelling 2 weeks after inguinal hernia repair with mesh (arrowheads) shows a heterogeneous hyperattenuating inguinal hematoma (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image in a 78-year-old man taking blood thinner medication who had pelvic pain 5 days after inguinal hernia repair. The urinary bladder (<b>*</b>) is displaced by a large hematoma with a hematocrit level (arrow), containing a focus of active contrast material extravasation (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig14b.jpeg" height="1323" width="1324" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span>. Hematoma in two different patients. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image in a 60-year-old man with pain and swelling 2 weeks after inguinal hernia repair with mesh (arrowheads) shows a heterogeneous hyperattenuating inguinal hematoma (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image in a 78-year-old man taking blood thinner medication who had pelvic pain 5 days after inguinal hernia repair. The urinary bladder (<b>*</b>) is displaced by a large hematoma with a hematocrit level (arrow), containing a focus of active contrast material extravasation (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig15.jpeg" height="750" width="750" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span>. Mesh colostomy with recurrent hernia. Axial nonenhanced CT image in a 68-year-old man who presented with bulging at an ostomy site 3 years after parastomal hernia mesh repair. A recurrent hernia (arrow) compresses the colostomy anteriorly (arrowhead). The mesh is invisible.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig16.jpeg" height="692" width="750" aria-labelledby="fig16" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16</span>. Failure of mesh repair in a 68-year-old woman who underwent mesh repair of a large hiatal hernia 7 years earlier and presented with a cough. Axial nonenhanced CT image shows a recurrent hernia with an intrathoracic stomach and a gastropleural fistula with a gastric wall defect (arrowhead) adjacent to the collapsed detached mesh (arrow) in extravasated enteric contrast material in the pleural space (black <b>*</b>). There is also a gas component in the loculated hydropneumothorax (white *).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig16">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig17.jpeg" height="750" width="750" aria-labelledby="fig17" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17</span>. Normal ventral mesh rectopexy in a 43-year-old man. Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image shows the normal anatomy of ventral mesh rectopexy. The mesh is attached to the sacral promontory (arrow) and anterior rectum (arrowhead). No inflammatory changes can be seen surrounding the mesh.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig17">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig18.jpeg" height="675" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig18" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18</span>. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image in the same patient as in <a href="#fig17">Figure 17</a>, who was evaluated for persistent pain after staple hemorrhoidopexy. The mesh is surrounded by new soft tissue (arrow) and has eroded through the rectal wall (arrowhead). Erosion was confirmed with sigmoidoscopy, and the patient underwent repair with removal of the mesh.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig18">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig19.jpeg" height="579" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig19" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19</span>. Photograph shows a polypropylene retropubic midurethral sling. The plastic sheaths are removed during surgery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig19">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig20.jpeg" height="1500" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig20" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20</span>. Illustration shows an axial superior view of the location of the arms of a midurethral sling placed with suprapubic (dashed line) and transvaginal (dotted line) approaches. In the suprapubic approach, the arms of the sling are located 1 cm from the midline. In the transvaginal approach, the arms of the sling are farther apart, approximately 2.5 cm from the midline. The urethra (arrow) and vagina (arrowhead) are shown.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig20">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig21.jpeg" height="651" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig21" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21</span>. Photograph shows a polypropylene transobturator tape. The long blue filament (arrows) is used during placement of the mesh.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig21">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig22a.jpeg" height="1307" width="1155" aria-labelledby="fig22a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22a</span>. Midurethral sling in a 46-year-old woman. Axial <b>(a)</b> and sagittal <b>(b)</b> T2-weighted MR images show the typical hypointense appearance of the sling material (arrowheads) in its normal location, wrapping around the urethra, with the arms coursing over the pubic bone and into the subcutaneous suprapubic fat.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig22a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig22b.jpeg" height="1308" width="1492" aria-labelledby="fig22b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22b</span>. Midurethral sling in a 46-year-old woman. Axial <b>(a)</b> and sagittal <b>(b)</b> T2-weighted MR images show the typical hypointense appearance of the sling material (arrowheads) in its normal location, wrapping around the urethra, with the arms coursing over the pubic bone and into the subcutaneous suprapubic fat.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig22b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig23.jpeg" height="586" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig23" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23</span>. Urine leak after placement of a midurethral sling in a 58-year-old woman. Axial CT cystogram shows the urinary bladder (<b>*</b>) with adjacent extravasated contrast material in the space of Retzius (arrows), an appearance referred to as the “molar tooth sign.”<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig23">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig24.jpeg" height="625" width="1000" aria-labelledby="fig24" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24</span>. Photograph of transvaginal polypropylene mesh shows one of the many types of vaginal mesh that were available before the 2019 U.S. FDA ban.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig24">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig25.jpeg" height="1900" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig25" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25</span>. Illustration of vaginal mesh with components placed along both anterior and posterior vaginal walls. Mesh arms extend through the obturator foramens (arrows) and sacrococcygeal ligaments (arrowhead). All vaginal mesh kits were recently removed from the market by the U.S. FDA.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig25">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig26" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig26.jpeg" height="1125" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig26" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 26</span>. Photograph shows sacrocolpopexy polypropylene mesh with the Y configuration.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig26">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig27" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig27.jpeg" height="750" width="750" aria-labelledby="fig27" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 27</span>. Normal sacrocolpopexy in a 50-year-old woman who previously underwent hysterectomy. Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image shows the normal anatomy of the sacrocolpopexy linear mesh attached to the sacral promontory (arrowhead) superiorly and the vaginal apex (arrow) inferiorly.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig27">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig28" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig28.jpeg" height="750" width="698" aria-labelledby="fig28" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 28</span>. Pelvic seroma in a 42-year-old woman who presented with swelling at the incision site 10 days after she underwent sacrocolpopexy and placement of a midurethral sling. Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image shows the urinary bladder (white <b>*</b>), a subcutaneous fluid collection (arrow), and a presacral fluid collection (black *) with a focus of gas (arrowhead). The sling and sacrocolpopexy mesh are not visible. Aspiration showed sterile seromas.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig28">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig29a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig29a.jpeg" height="1619" width="1619" aria-labelledby="fig29a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 29a</span>. Uterine cuff abscess at MRI and US in a 50-year-old woman after hysterectomy and sacrocolpopexy. Sagittal T2-weighted <b>(a)</b> and T1-weighted fat-saturated contrast-enhanced <b>(b)</b> MR images and sagittal transvaginal US image <b>(c)</b> rotated to match the patient orientation on the MR images show the sacrocolpopexy mesh posterior to the vagina as a thin hypointense line (arrows in <b>a</b>) and a dashed hyperechoic line (arrowheads in <b>c</b>). A T2-hyperintense rim-enhancing abscess (<b>*</b>) is seen at the vaginal cuff (☆) and is also demonstrated as a complex fluid collection (<b>*</b>) with through transmission.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig29a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig29b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig29b.jpeg" height="1613" width="1616" aria-labelledby="fig29b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 29b</span>. Uterine cuff abscess at MRI and US in a 50-year-old woman after hysterectomy and sacrocolpopexy. Sagittal T2-weighted <b>(a)</b> and T1-weighted fat-saturated contrast-enhanced <b>(b)</b> MR images and sagittal transvaginal US image <b>(c)</b> rotated to match the patient orientation on the MR images show the sacrocolpopexy mesh posterior to the vagina as a thin hypointense line (arrows in <b>a</b>) and a dashed hyperechoic line (arrowheads in <b>c</b>). A T2-hyperintense rim-enhancing abscess (<b>*</b>) is seen at the vaginal cuff (☆) and is also demonstrated as a complex fluid collection (<b>*</b>) with through transmission.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig29b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig29c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig29c.jpeg" height="1647" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig29c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 29c</span>. Uterine cuff abscess at MRI and US in a 50-year-old woman after hysterectomy and sacrocolpopexy. Sagittal T2-weighted <b>(a)</b> and T1-weighted fat-saturated contrast-enhanced <b>(b)</b> MR images and sagittal transvaginal US image <b>(c)</b> rotated to match the patient orientation on the MR images show the sacrocolpopexy mesh posterior to the vagina as a thin hypointense line (arrows in <b>a</b>) and a dashed hyperechoic line (arrowheads in <b>c</b>). A T2-hyperintense rim-enhancing abscess (<b>*</b>) is seen at the vaginal cuff (☆) and is also demonstrated as a complex fluid collection (<b>*</b>) with through transmission.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig29c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig30a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig30a.jpeg" height="1063" width="1440" aria-labelledby="fig30a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 30a</span>. Illustrations show pelvic mesh for postprostatectomy urinary incontinence. The bulbourethral sling <b>(a)</b> and the transobturator sling <b>(b)</b> diagrams show retropubic and transobturator arm positioning, respectively. The arms are secured to each other across the midline. The bone-anchored sling <b>(c)</b> is a central mesh that is secured to the inferior pubic rami. The quadratic sling <b>(d)</b> has lateral transobturator arms and anterior prepubic arms, which self-anchor to the soft tissues.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig30a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig30b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig30b.jpeg" height="1065" width="1439" aria-labelledby="fig30b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 30b</span>. Illustrations show pelvic mesh for postprostatectomy urinary incontinence. The bulbourethral sling <b>(a)</b> and the transobturator sling <b>(b)</b> diagrams show retropubic and transobturator arm positioning, respectively. The arms are secured to each other across the midline. The bone-anchored sling <b>(c)</b> is a central mesh that is secured to the inferior pubic rami. The quadratic sling <b>(d)</b> has lateral transobturator arms and anterior prepubic arms, which self-anchor to the soft tissues.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig30b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig30c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig30c.jpeg" height="1066" width="1465" aria-labelledby="fig30c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 30c</span>. Illustrations show pelvic mesh for postprostatectomy urinary incontinence. The bulbourethral sling <b>(a)</b> and the transobturator sling <b>(b)</b> diagrams show retropubic and transobturator arm positioning, respectively. The arms are secured to each other across the midline. The bone-anchored sling <b>(c)</b> is a central mesh that is secured to the inferior pubic rami. The quadratic sling <b>(d)</b> has lateral transobturator arms and anterior prepubic arms, which self-anchor to the soft tissues.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig30c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig30d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig30d.jpeg" height="1061" width="1462" aria-labelledby="fig30d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 30d</span>. Illustrations show pelvic mesh for postprostatectomy urinary incontinence. The bulbourethral sling <b>(a)</b> and the transobturator sling <b>(b)</b> diagrams show retropubic and transobturator arm positioning, respectively. The arms are secured to each other across the midline. The bone-anchored sling <b>(c)</b> is a central mesh that is secured to the inferior pubic rami. The quadratic sling <b>(d)</b> has lateral transobturator arms and anterior prepubic arms, which self-anchor to the soft tissues.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig30d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig31a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig31a.jpeg" height="1235" width="1235" aria-labelledby="fig31a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 31a</span>. Detached infected bone-anchored sling for postprostatectomy urinary incontinence in a 68-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows the transverse location of the bone-anchored sling meshoma (arrowheads) between the inferior pubic rami and suture anchors (arrows), which are attached to the bilateral inferior pubic rami. <b>(b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image acquired 4 years later when the patient presented with pus draining from the perineum shows a detached right suture anchor (straight arrow) and soft tissue around the mesh now extending inferiorly beyond the field of view of the image (curved arrow). <b>(c)</b> Coronal T2-weighted MR image shows the mesh as a dotted hypointense line (arrows) that is detached from the right inferior pubic ramus (<b>*</b>) and extends inferiorly into the perineal soft tissues.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig31a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig31b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig31b.jpeg" height="1235" width="1235" aria-labelledby="fig31b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 31b</span>. Detached infected bone-anchored sling for postprostatectomy urinary incontinence in a 68-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows the transverse location of the bone-anchored sling meshoma (arrowheads) between the inferior pubic rami and suture anchors (arrows), which are attached to the bilateral inferior pubic rami. <b>(b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image acquired 4 years later when the patient presented with pus draining from the perineum shows a detached right suture anchor (straight arrow) and soft tissue around the mesh now extending inferiorly beyond the field of view of the image (curved arrow). <b>(c)</b> Coronal T2-weighted MR image shows the mesh as a dotted hypointense line (arrows) that is detached from the right inferior pubic ramus (<b>*</b>) and extends inferiorly into the perineal soft tissues.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig31b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig31c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190106/asset/images/large/rg.2020190106.fig31c.jpeg" height="1235" width="1233" aria-labelledby="fig31c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 31c</span>. Detached infected bone-anchored sling for postprostatectomy urinary incontinence in a 68-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows the transverse location of the bone-anchored sling meshoma (arrowheads) between the inferior pubic rami and suture anchors (arrows), which are attached to the bilateral inferior pubic rami. <b>(b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image acquired 4 years later when the patient presented with pus draining from the perineum shows a detached right suture anchor (straight arrow) and soft tissue around the mesh now extending inferiorly beyond the field of view of the image (curved arrow). <b>(c)</b> Coronal T2-weighted MR image shows the mesh as a dotted hypointense line (arrows) that is detached from the right inferior pubic ramus (<b>*</b>) and extends inferiorly into the perineal soft tissues.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190106&amp;id=fig31c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul